                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="codex">
                            <supportDesc material="perg">
                                <support>
                                    <p>
                                        <material>Parchment</material>.</p>
                                </support>
                                <extent>3. <dimensions scope="all" type="leaf">
                                        <height>215</height>
                                        <width>147</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </extent>
                                <condition>
                                    <p>The 3 leaves are not well preserved. The lower half of f. 1
                                        has several holes and the most part of the last 3 lines is
                                        torn away. f. 2 has also holes and the outer part has been
                                        cut away, and f. 3 is damaged both by ploughing and wear.
                                        All the damages has caused a loss of text.</p>
                                </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="1" writtenLines="39">
                                    <p>The manuscript is written in long lines with 39 lines to the
                                        page. On f. 1v, the trace of a rubric is found. An effaced
                                        red majuscule on 2 lines is found on f. 1v.</p>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin notBefore="1276" notAfter="1300" cert="high" evidence="conjecture">
                            <p>The manuscript is written in <origPlace>Iceland</origPlace> in
                                    <origDate notBefore="1275" notAfter="1300" cert="high"
                                    evidence="conjecture">the fourth quarter of the thirteenth
                                    century</origDate> (<bibl>
                                    <ref target="FragmHelleJensen">Jensen 1979</ref>
                                    <biblScope unit="page">45</biblScope>
                                </bibl>). Kålund's dating: <date notBefore="1200" notAfter="1299"
                                    >the thirteenth century</date> (<bibl>Kålund: <ref type="secondary-1" target="KKKat"
                                        >Katalog</ref>
                                        <biblScope unit="volume">I</biblScope>
                                        <biblScope unit="page">561</biblScope>
                                    </bibl>).</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Nothing is known about the provenance and history of fol. 1. According to <bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary" target="FMS9">Fornmanna sögur</ref>
                                    <biblScope unit="volume">IX</biblScope>
                                </bibl> fols 2-3 were put in a cover on which <name type="person"
                                    key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> had written: <q
                                    xml:lang="is">Þesse .2. innlgd bld eru fundin i <country
                                        key="NO">Noregi</country>. Eg hefi feinged þau af <name
                                        type="person" key="AsgJon001">Asgeiri Jonssyne</name>,
                                        en<expan>n</expan> hann feck þau fra Hr. <name type="person"
                                        key="TruNit001">Truid Nitter</name>, presti i Norðlndum,
                                    hver þau hafdi tekit fra stulku einne, er þau ætladi ad bruka
                                    til at sauma ä. Fyrra bladed er ur <hi rend="underline">Sverris
                                        Sgu</hi> hid sidara er ur <hi rend="underline">Appendice
                                        Sverris</hi>-Sgu druvïs samsettre, en<expan>n</expan> vær
                                        almen<expan>n</expan>elega hfum. Og mä þ<expan>et</expan>ta
                                    sidara blad halldast f<expan>iri</expan> raritet. NB. Þetta blad
                                    accorderar vid þä Dönsku version nærre lage.</q>
                            </p>
                            <p>Louis-Jensen (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary" target="BiblArn32">Louis Jensen 1977</ref>
                                    <biblScope unit="page">20</biblScope>
                                </bibl>) however, is more inclined to think that this cover belonged
                                to <ref type="ms" target="#AM04-0325-VIII-4-c-en">AM 325 VIII 4 c
                                    4to</ref>. </p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
